properties.comment: Built in 1916, this 12-story building is known for its architectural beauty and prominence among Park Avenue's vast stretch of apartments.
The southernmost building on Fifth Avenue, overlooking the Metropolitan Museum of Art. It was built in 1925-1926 and is one of the city’s earliest co-operative apartment buildings.
Known for its exceptionally large apartments, there are fifteen stories but only one apartment per floor. Built in 1916.
Known for its flamboyantly detailed Gothic architecture and cast-iron railings, built in 1928.

Known for its luxury design and as one of the finest pre-war era apartment buildings in the neighborhood. It was designed by J.E.R. Carpenter – the leading designer of luxury apartment buildings in the 20th century. Built in 1914.
Known as "the heart of Harlem," and assembled by J. Henry Clark who was among the wealthiest men in early Harlem, built in 1903.
Known for its opulent Beaux-Arts style and entrance gateway, built in 1902.
An Art Deco apartment building built in 1927 often associated with its notable residents.
Popular due to its classic architectural design, constructed in 1907.
Constructed in 1929, this high-rise building held the title of being the tallest building in the world upon completion.
The building became a model for all subsequent upscale apartment buildings in New York City. Built in 1910-1912 and designed by McKim, Mead & White.
One of New York's earliest co-op apartment buildings, completed in 1927.
Historically significant Beaux-Arts style apartment building built in 1908, part of the Fort Washington Avenue Historic District.
The art-deco building constructed in 1905 has a unique and iconic architecture, in a neighborhood otherwise known for its brownstone rowhouses.
Completed in 1930, one of the most prestigious addresses in New York City, iconic for its twin towers.
Known as an architectural gem and one of the first ever high-rise apartment buildings in New York City, originally constructed in 1869.
It was famous for its resident actors and association with the theatre industry, built in the mid-19th century.
The oldest surviving synagogue building in New York City, constructed in 1850.
is new each year.
A fraternal organization promoting Puerto Rican culture, active since at least 1949.
Constructed in 1886, housed many important Italian American organizations.
Founded in the mid-1940s in the honor of war veteran Benjamin Ralph Kimlau who died during World War II. Regarded as a significant part of Chinese American history.
Operating since the 1870s. Initially a social service and housing organization, it later served as a temporary home for Chinese immigrants.
Famous for its local contributions as a YMCA center, built in 1932. It did have overnight rooms, thus functioned similarly to a hotel for many.
The building is notable for its former occupants including painter Mark Rothko and writer William S. Burroughs. Founded in 1885.

properties.dName: Kaiser, F. E. Co. Motor Repairs

properties.comment: Known for being one of NYC's earliest skyscrapers with Eastern European influence, constructed in 1912.
Built in 1887, it has a Byzantine Revival architectural style. Did serve as a spiritual center for Greek immigrants.
A landmark church built in 1938, known for its beautiful Georgian Revival architecture.

properties.dName: Church of Mary Help of Christians
properties.comment: Opened in 1917, it served predominately Irish and Italian Catholics.
Landmark Roman Catholic parish church and the home of the Missionaries of the Most Holy Redeemer, inaugurated in 1847.
A notable Episcopal church built in 1929 known for its stained glass, woodwork, and Casavant Freres pipe organ.

properties.dName: Church of the Most Precious Blood
properties.comment: Established in 1887, it is a historic Catholic Parish.
Established in 1901 and significant to the religious community of Hamilton Heights.
Known for being where the renowned author Thomas Merton was baptized. The church was built in 1906.
Known for its classic, European-style architecture, constructed in 1843.
A significant center of worship for Jewish immigrants from Romania, established in 1885.
This church is a historic African Methodist Episcopal Zion church. Built in 1920, it played important roles in African-American social and political movements.
Known as the common headquarters of several Christian denominations and offices of ecumenical organizations. Opened in 1948.
Historic building with architectural significance; built in 1892.
Famous for hosting Norwegian seamen during World War II, constructed in 1931.
A Roman Catholic Church built in 1884 serving as a significant religious and spiritual center in Spanish Harlem.

Also known as 'The Park', the church was built in 1911 and houses one of New York City's most outstanding pipe organs and a beautiful stained glass collection. While it's not a skyscraper by any means, as a church steeple, it had a significant height.
Noted for its large size and elaborate Neo-Gothic architecture, it was completed in 1930 and is one of the leading centers of progressive Christianity.
Known for its beautiful stained glass, built in 1891.
A prominent example of Roman Catholic Gothic Revival architecture built in 1898.
Raised in 1838. This church is known for its early Gothic Revival style, designed by Clement Clarke Moore.
Noted for its wide outreach programs and highly active congregation, though it technically an influential religious institution rather than a club. Founded in 1987.
Constructed in 1827, it was a central religious establishment in the Lower East Side, even acting as a stop on the Underground Railroad during the Civil War.
Built in 1892, it's one of the oldest churches in the neighborhood and a good example of Dutch-colonial Revival architecture.
Known for creating traditional New York-style bagels, founded in 1937.
The hotel was famous due to its grandeur and association with the railroad, established in 1926.
This historic hotel was opened in 1904 and known for its grand architecture. It was renovated and reopened as the Ace Hotel in 2009.
Famous for its cafe which was a key venue for the bohemian scene, hosting many famous artists and intellectuals, including Jackson Pollock and Dylan Thomas; Built in 1925.
First established as a hotel in 1851 and has remained an operating hotel since. It is known for its authentic 19th-century architecture.
Famous Art Deco Skyscraper; a hotel built in 1931.
Known for its European style and classic accommodations, built in 1930.
Built in the 1920s as the Henry Hudson Hotel.
Though famed for its modernistic architecture, the actual building dates back to the 1940s. It is well-known for having a rooftop pool.
Originally constructed in 1927 as the Hotel Beverly, it was a famed hotel of its time.
Known for its distinct architecture built in the French Second Empire Style. Constructed in 1905.
Known for its impressive structure and for hosting several renowned personalities in the 1930s.
Known as a long-lasting fixture of the Murray Hill neighborhood, the exact construction date is not clear but it existed in the 1940s.
Noteworthy for its ornate terracotta detailing and connection to the theatre district. Built in 1903.
Known for its 12 luxury rooms in two restored townhouses dated back to the 1830s.
Originally the Murray Hill Hotel built in 1863, it was a prominent fixture of New York architecture.
Originally built as the National Maritime Union in 1966, it became an iconic symbol of the modern architectural style in Chelsea.
Opened in 1927, this hotel is known for its stunning design and architecture, as well as its mul-Michelin-starred restaurant.
Opened in 1903. First hotel in New York to provide housing for professional women exclusively.
Opened in 1930 and quickly became a beacon of the city due to its impressive size, Art Deco design, and proximity to Penn Station.
An elegant boutique hotel marked by its classic architecture. Existing since the early 20th century.
might have existed at this time—it was a flophouse accommodating hundreds of men in tiny cabins. But it is unclear whether it was famous before 1950 or its exact age.
Known for its historic charm and as a staple in the area, established in 1926.

properties.address: West 123rd St & Adam Clayton Powell Jr. Blvd
properties.comment: Architecturally significant hotel built in gothic revival style in Harlem. Built in the 1920s.
Charted in the late 19th century as one of the last remaining flophouses in the area.
Built in 1899, this Beaux-Arts style building is known for maintaining its historical charm and welcoming famous personalities.
This was a renowned nightclub in the 1940s which was a popular spot for celebrities and socialites. Established in 1931.
Opened in 1906 and it's one of the oldest Italian restaurants in NYC, it's known for its elegant garden and rich history.
Opened in 1923, it was a well known dining place for the wealthy social circle.
Operated as both a tavern and a museum, it's famous as a prominent meeting place in the Revolutionary War era. It was established in 1762.
Opened in 1908, gained fame for its authentic Italian cuisine and guest appearances in movies and TV shows.
Popular for their coal-fired brick oven pizza since 1929; considered among the best pizzerias in NYC.
Among the first pizzerias in Yorkville, it was built in the 1940s.
Famous for its burgers and bar food, established in 1884
Established in 1908, this shop specialized in homemade mozzarella and pasta.
Traditionally designed Viennese Restaurant established in the late 1930s
Family-run Italian restaurant known for its classic dishes. Opened in 1941, it quickly gained a loyal following.
Known for its cheap, hearty Cantonese food since 1938, it is one of the oldest and most beloved restaurants in Chinatown.
Significant education center, built in 1923.
Known for providing an academic education to young people pursuing careers in the performing arts, entertainment, or competitive sports, founded in 1914.
Named after Irish patriot Robert Emmet, the school building was constructed in 1905.
Opened in 1901, it was initially a casino and became known for presenting vaudeville shows in Chinese.
A theater active in the mid-19th century providing minstrel shows.
Established in 1805, Chatham Theatre was famous for its variety shows, dramas, comic operas, and Shakespearean tragedies. It was one of the best affordable theaters of its time.
Built in the mid-19th century and was a famed venue for many German-language plays.
Opened in 1845, it was famous for its 'mirror curtain' that descended to the stage level at the conclusion of the performances. This novel idea was copied by other theaters.
Known for being a center for Hebrew theatre, established in 1881.
Opened in 1826, it was known as the birthplace of American drama. It also ignited the 'Astor Place Riot' in 1849 due to rivalry between American and British actors.
An important venue for the Yiddish-speaking Romanian-Jewish community, built in 1903.
A classic theatre known for drama performances built in the mid-1800s.
